1. Broadcasting
Broadcasting allows NumPy to perform arithmetic between arrays of different but compatible shapes. A scalar is virtually expanded across all elements without actually creating a new array.

Example:
import numpy as np
arr = np.array([10,20,30,40])
print(arr + 5)

Output:
[15 25 35 45]

2. Element-wise Operations

arr + 10   -> Add 10 to every element
arr - 1    -> Subtract 1 from every element
arr * 2    -> Multiply every element
arr / 2    -> Divide every element
arr ** 2   -> Square each element
arr ** 3   -> Cube each element

3. Array + Array Operations

a = np.array([1,2,3])
b = np.array([10,20,30])

a + b -> [11 22 33]
a * b -> [10 40 90]

4. 2D Arrays (Matrices)

matrix = np.array([
    [1,2,3],
    [4,5,6]
])

shape -> (2,3)
ndim  -> 2
size  -> 6

5. Indexing 2D Arrays

matrix[row, column]

matrix[0]     -> First row
matrix[1]     -> Second row
matrix[1,2]   -> 6
matrix[:,1]   -> Second column
matrix[0,:]   -> First row

6. Matrix Operations

A + B  -> Element-wise addition
A * B  -> Element-wise multiplication
A @ B  -> Matrix multiplication
np.matmul(A,B) -> Matrix multiplication

7. Useful Functions

marks.shape
marks.ndim
marks.size
marks.mean()
marks.max()
marks.min()

8. Common Mistakes

❌ marks[1] -> Second row
✅ marks[:,1] -> Second column

❌ A * B is NOT matrix multiplication.
✅ A @ B or np.matmul(A,B) performs matrix multiplication.
